         <t:abstract>
            <t:p>The <t:foreign xml:lang="gez">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</t:foreign>  is a version of the <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1961Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</t:ref>, a Church service made up of psalms, biblical readings and hymns. 
               It includes the entire <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2701Dawit">Psalter</t:ref> in its daily pensum.  Its witnesses "with no psalms at compline or in the midnight office, but with thirty psalms and three canticles in each of the other five hours" 
               <t:bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/DZFI5RB2"><seg type="book"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/><title level="m">The liturgy of the hours in East and West: the origins of the Divine Office and its meaning for today</title><author><forename>Robert F.</forename><surname>Taft</surname></author><pubPlace>Collegeville, Minn.</pubPlace><publisher>The Liturgical Pr.</publisher><date>1986</date><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:Taft1986Liturgy</note></note><note type="tag">bm:Taft1986Liturgy</note><t:citedRange unit="page">270</t:citedRange></t:bibl> follow the Ethiopian distribution of the psalter.</t:p>
            <t:p>The three other types of <t:foreign xml:lang="gez">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</t:foreign> identified by  <t:bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/DZFI5RB2"><seg type="book"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/><title level="m">The liturgy of the hours in East and West: the origins of the Divine Office and its meaning for today</title><author><forename>Robert F.</forename><surname>Taft</surname></author><pubPlace>Collegeville, Minn.</pubPlace><publisher>The Liturgical Pr.</publisher><date>1986</date><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:Taft1986Liturgy</note></note><note type="tag">bm:Taft1986Liturgy</note><t:citedRange unit="page">266</t:citedRange></t:bibl> are: </t:p>
            <t:p> 
               <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2230Saatat">Saʿātāt za-gǝbṣ</t:ref>: the Coptic Saʿātāt;</t:p>
            <t:p> 
               <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT3575Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</t:ref>: the Saʿātāt of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4709Giyorgis">Giyorgis of Saglā</t:persName>, 
               which replaced the <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2230Saatat">Saʿātāt za-gǝbṣ</t:ref>:  and is presently in use in Ethiopia and Eritrea;</t:p>
            <t:p>
               <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT3577GizeS">Gize ṣalot</t:ref>: a cursus of prayers which is not really a <t:foreign xml:lang="gez">Saʿātāt</t:foreign>, but a
               <t:foreign xml:lang="gez">Gize ṣalot</t:foreign> for hermits and recluses.</t:p>
           <t:p>
